<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Celebrates Asian American Heritage Month in April</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Zenaida Gonzalez Kotala
		
		<span class="date">April 13, 2007</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:zkotala@mail.ucf.edu">Zenaida Gonzalez Kotala</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6120</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.apac.ucf.edu">Asian American Heritage Month</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>University of Central Florida students are celebrating Asian American Heritage Month in April.</p><p>Several public events featuring speakers and highlighting cultures from Vietnam to the Philippines are planned throughout the month. The goal is to create a better understanding of the cultural, social and political aspects of the Asian-American identity.</p><p>The national recognition of Asian American Heritage Month occurs in May, but the Asian Pacific American Coalition at UCF planned the celebration in April because the spring semester ends during the first week of May. </p><p>The Asian Pacific American Coalition Â– in addition to the Asian Student Association, Filipino Student Association, Vietnam American Student Association, Delta Phi Lambda and FM Interest Group -- partnered with several groups on and off campus to sponsor the events. All of the events are free and open to the public.</p><p>Coalition chair Ricky Ly said the monthlong celebration is a way to look at the many challenges that face the Asian-American community. Examples include the Model Minority Myth, stereotypes in the media, cultural identity issues, generational gaps, social justice and civil rights, and immigration laws. By addressing the issues, he hopes to develop a better understanding among the entire UCF and Central Florida communities.</p><p>Â“It is essential that we celebrate Asian American Heritage Month because for far too long our community has been silent about the history of Americans of Asian decent,Â” Ly said. Â“Growing up as a minority, we hardly ever get the opportunity to learn about the struggles or hear the stories about why we are here today.Â”</p><p>UCF is not alone in these kinds of celebrations. </p><p>As the population of Asian-Americans has grown, so has interest in their many cultures and customs. In Florida alone, the population has grown to more than 371,385 in 2005, according to the American Community Survey, an arm of the U.S. Census. At UCF, there are about 2,000 undergraduate students who identify themselves as Asian or Pacific Islanders. That includes students from the Philippines, Vietnam and China.</p><p>Most major cities in the United States celebrate Asian culture and contributions in May. The first federal recognition of the contributions Asian-Americans have made came in June 1977, when Reps. Frank Horton of New York and Norman Mineta of California introduced a House resolution that called for an Asian/Pacific Heritage Week. In October 1978, President Jimmy Carter signed a joint resolution designating the annual celebration nationwide.</p><p>President George H.W. Bush expanded the recognition into a monthlong affair in May 1990 and called it Asian Pacific American Heritage Month. </p><p>To find out more about the various events during Asian American Heritage Month at UCF, visit <a href="http://www.apac.ucf.edu">http://www.apac.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

